# Documentation and examples sync

When work changes **behavior**, **public API**, **CLI usage**, **configuration**, or **contributor workflow**, update the relevant artifacts in the same change set (or follow-up commit) so users and contributors are not misled.

## What to touch

| Artifact | Update when |
|----------|-------------|
| `README.md` | Install/usage, API surface, options, or quickstart change |
| `examples/` | A new pattern is worth demonstrating, or an example is wrong or outdated |
| `CHANGELOG.md` | User-visible fix, feature, or breaking change (follow existing section style) |
| `CONTRIBUTING.md` | PR/process, test commands, or dev setup change |
| `docs/` | Deeper reference or placeholder/grammar docs need to match implementation |

## Rules

- Prefer **one PR** that includes code/tests **and** doc/example updates when the change is user-facing.
- If you only fix internals with **no** observable change, do **not** pad CHANGELOG or README.
- **Examples** must run or stay accurate: if you change flags or imports, update `examples/` and any README inside example folders.
- After edits, spot-check that links and file paths in README and docs still exist.

## Do not

- Add or expand markdown files outside this set unless the task explicitly asks for new docs.
- Leave stale “coming soon” or contradictory statements next to updated code.
